conf_long = conf %>% select(t2$var, school_id) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = t2$var, names_to = "t2")


cl_sch = conf_long %>% group_by(school_id) %>%
  summarize(n_tag = sum(value))
cl_tag = conf_long %>% group_by(t2) %>%
  summarize(n_sch = sum(value))

gridExtra::grid.arrange(

    geom_histogram(binwidth = 4) +
    labs(x = "Number of schools", y = "Number of tags") +
    expand_limits(x = 0),
  ggplot(cl_sch, aes(x = n_tag)) +

Clustering T2 Tags

Let’s look at the correlations between the Tier 2 tags:

conf_cor = conf %>%
  select(t2$var) %>%
  cor

ggcorrplot(conf_cor, hc.order = T, type = "upper") +
  scale_fill_distiller(type = "div", limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  theme(axis.text=element_blank())
## Scale for 'fill' is already present. Adding another scale for 'fill',
## which will replace the existing scale.

cor_df = conf_cor %>%
  as.table %>%
  as.data.frame %>%
  arrange(desc(Freq)) %>%
  rename(Correlation = Freq) %>%
  filter(as.integer(Var1) < as.integer(Var2))
    
ggplot(cor_df, aes(x = Correlation)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.03)

Unsurprisingly, mostly positive correlations. measures_sel and measures_climate have an extremely high correlation of 0.87

We’ll start off with trying a few clustering methods. First, hierarchical agglomerative clustering, then exploratory factor analysis. We will also look at the data as a graph with weighted edges, and use community detection algori. For now, we’ll work on the confirmed data.

Agglomerative clustering

conf_hclust = conf %>% 
  select(t2$var) %>% 
  t %>% 
  dist %>%
  hclust(method = "ward.D2")

gg_hc = conf_hclust %>% dendro_data(type = "triangle")

hc_labs = gg_hc %>%
  label %>%
  left_join(select(t2, var, t1_alt), by = c("label" = "var"))
## Warning: Column `label`/`var` joining factor and character vector, coercing
## into character vector
ggplot() +
  geom_segment(data = segment(gg_hc), aes(x, y, xend = xend, yend = yend)) +
  geom_text(data = hc_labs, aes(x, y, label = label, color = t1_alt), hjust = 0, size = 4) +
  coord_flip(clip = "off") +
  scale_color_tableau(name = "Alternate grouping") +
  scale_y_reverse(expand = expand_scale(mult = c(0, 0.5), add = c(0, 2))) +
  theme_dendro()

The Ward distance metric seems pretty good - might be worth trying out some others (definitely Jaccard, maybe Manhattan). Euclidean didn’t seem as sensible.
